properties.name: Mt. Rainier National Park
properties.description: Ascending to 14,410 feet above sea level, Mount Rainier stands as an icon in the Washington landscape. An active volcano, Mount Rainier is the most glaciated peak in the contiguous U.S.A., spawning five major rivers. Subalpine wildflower meadows ring the icy volcano while ancient forest cloaks Mount Rainierâ€™s lower slopes.

properties.name: Spanaway Park
properties.description: This 135-acre park along beautiful Spanaway Lake is extremely popular with many year-round activities. Visitors to the park can explore a multitude of aquatic recreation opportunities including two swimming beaches (no lifeguards), a boat launch, a fishing pier, handicapped accessible bathrooms, a new picnic area by the south swimming beach, newly renovated boat ramp, ADA playground equipment with a seating plaza for parents and a new three mile trail system by Little Spanaway Lake.

properties.name: Dawson Playfield
properties.description: Dawson Playfield is a place to play multiple sports. It is located at East 90th Street and Portland Avenue in Tacoma. The park includes a covered picnic shelter without cooking facilities, lighted softball field (non-regulation), outdoor basketball and tennis courts, playground equipment, uncovered picnic tables and walking track.

properties.name: Lake Spanaway Golf Course
properties.description: Lake Spanaway Golf Course is part of the Spanaway Regional Recreational Complex that also contains Bresemann Forest, Sprinkler Recreation Center and Spanaway Park. Lake Spanaway is a majestic golf course carved out of a forest of native firs that truly is a great test of golf. The greens are large and the breaks are somewhat subtle at times. This is a challenging, yet fair, golf course for golfers of all levels and ages

properties.description: This diverse section of trail, at almost 11 miles, is the longest section of the Foothills route. This trail is approximately 0.6 mile long and ends at 91st Avenue Court SW in the Tiffany Park development.  The other trail begins at Kobayashi Park in the City of University Place and travels west along the creek for approximately 0.5 mile.
